<span lang=&quot;en-US&quot; style=&quot;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:12pt;text-transform:none;font-weight:normal;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;line-height:200%;mso-spacerun:yes;&quot;>
&nbsp; So many men did it – did his father ever mention the poor? – no, save the inevitable comment – with a glance at his wife – that no man was poor who was happily married.&nbsp; Laurence thought of the men at his club, who would have passed Mary in the street, never inviting her in, sure that they deserved privilege, that their souls had existed before death and had been promoted to privilege on birthright, that the poor were unworthy and they themselves were made virtuous by being dropped from infinity into their golden cribs.&nbsp; A strange revulsion arose in Laurence, a revulsion against self and society, against the whole sickly lie of unearned privilege – and then Lydia’s face rose before him, blotting out the gray smoky London street, soothing the numb jostling of the carriage.</span>
</p>

<p style=&quot;text-align:left;page-break-inside:auto;page-break-after:auto;page-break-before:avoid;line-height:200%;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent:14.4pt;&quot;>
